06930nam a22012135i 9780691202112DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020012702  a97806912021127 a10.1515/97806912021122doi  a(DE-B1597)550760  a(OCoLC)1145922390  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aE184.A1b.A453 2020 4aE184.A1bA453 2020 7aSOC0060002bisacsh04a305.8009732231 aAlba, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Great Demographic Illusion :bMajority, Minority, and the Expanding American Mainstream /cRichard Alba. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b15 b/w illus. 7 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: The Narrative of the Majority-Minority Society -- t2. The Enigma of November 2016 -- t3. The Power of the Demographic Imagination -- t4. The Demographic Data System and the Surge of Young Americans from Mixed Family Backgrounds -- t5. What We Know about Americans from Mixed Minority-White Families -- t6. Some Ideas and History for Understanding Today's Ethno-Racial Mixing -- t7. Assimilation in the Early Twenty-First Century -- t8. Social Policies to Broaden Mainstream Assimilation -- t9 Toward a New Understanding of American Possibilities -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tindex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhy the number of young Americans with ethno-racially mixed backgrounds is surging and what this means for the country's future Americans are under the spell of a distorted and polarizing story about their country's future-the majority-minority narrative-which contends that inevitable demographic changes will create a society with a majority made up of minorities for the first time in American history. The Great Demographic Illusion reveals the flaws in this narrative and how it obscures a more transformative development: the rising numbers of young Americans from ethno-racially mixed families, consisting of one white and one nonwhite parent. Examining the unprecedented significance of mixed parentage in the twenty-first-century United States, Richard Alba looks at how young Americans with this background will play pivotal roles in the country's demographic future.Assembling a vast body of evidence, Alba explores where these mixed families fit in American society. Most participate in the mainstream, as seen in their high levels of integration into social milieus with whites and frequent marriage with them. Yet, racism is also evident in the very different experiences of individuals with black-white heritage. Alba's portrait squares in key ways with the history of American immigrant-group assimilation, and indicates that, once again, mainstream American society is expanding and becoming more inclusive. He discusses social policies that might enhance mainstream assimilation and argues that the future is more likely to resemble a gradual evolution from the present rather than a stark overturning of an established order.An outlook on social change that counters more rigid demographic beliefs and predictions, The Great Demographic Illusion offers a new way of understanding American society and its coming transformation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aEthnic groupszUnited States. 0aMajorities. 0aMinoritieszUnited States. 0aRacially mixed peoplezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Demography.2bisacsh  aAfrican Americans.  aAmerican Indians.  aAsian Americans.  aAsians.  aEric Kaufmann.  aHispanics.  aLatinos.  aNative Americans.  aThe Diversity Explosion.  aU.S Census.  aWhiteshift.  aWillia